opposition to Exelon Corp.'s request to certify a second nuclear plant at <br>
its Clinton site.<br>
<br>
No New Nukes hopes to make the public and lawmakers aware of what organizers <br>
view as dangers associated with nuclear plants.<br>
<br>
Among concerns are nuclear-waste storage, security issues in light of <br>
possible terrorist attacks and studies that link health problems to exposure <br>
to low-level radiation surrounding nuclear plants, said Sandra Lindberg, a <br>
primary organizer of No New Nukes.<br>
<br>
Lindberg, of Normal and formerly of Clinton, teaches voice and acting as <br>
well as a class on actors as activists at Illinois Wesleyan University.<br>
<br>
She got involved in the nuclear issue after touring as an actress, becoming <br>
more and more concerned each time she visited a city with a nuclear plant <br>
nearby and opened the phone book to see an evacuation plan.<br>
<br>
&quot;I think of all the environmental hazards, this is the single most important <br>
issue to work on,&quot; said Lindberg, 46. &quot;Whatever we decide to do with this <br>
industry will be with us for thousands of years.&quot;<br>
<br>
No New Nukes meets at 3 p.m. today at the Ecology Action Center at 202 W. <br>
College Ave., Normal.<br>
<br>
Exelon spokeswoman Ann Mary Carley said the company welcomes a public <br>
discussion of nuclear issues.<br>
<br>
&quot;I believe strongly that nuclear power is safe and clean and reliable <br>
energy. But I can also respect another group's right to express their <br>
opinion. We're always willing to talk to folks,&quot; Carley said.<br>
<br>
Carley stressed no decision to build a second plant at Clinton has been <br>
made.<br>
<br>
&quot;But, by doing this, we are ahead of the game,&quot; she said.<br>
<br>
The process to receive Nuclear Regulatory Commission permission can take <br>
three years. The permit would allow Exelon to proceed with planning on <br>
environmental, safety and emergency issues before applying for an actual <br>
construction permit to build. The early site permit is in effect 20 years.<br>
<br>
Lindberg foresees a scenario in which Exelon may build a second plant to <br>
replace the aging one now in use. That Exelon has had a plant at the site <br>
for years in no way lessens concern over development of a second.<br>
<br>
&quot;I think there is a lot of new information about the hazards of nuclear <br>
plants that wasn't available then,&quot; she said.<br>
